{"generation_category":"sports_competition","candidates":[{"idiom_candidate":"throw the curve","proposed_meaning_en":"to surprise an opponent with an unexpected move","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Alludes to baseball's curveball as a metaphor for unpredictability."},{"idiom_candidate":"chase the buzzer","proposed_meaning_en":"to scramble under time pressure to succeed","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"american","notes":"References the buzzer signaling end of play in basketball."},{"idiom_candidate":"step on ice","proposed_meaning_en":"to take a risky move under pressure","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Evokes the instability of stepping on icy terrain in competitive situations."},{"idiom_candidate":"ride the whistle","proposed_meaning_en":"to push along as long as allowed before rules intervene","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"From referee's whistle indicating play boundaries."},{"idiom_candidate":"bend the play","proposed_meaning_en":"to manipulate a situation subtly to one's advantage","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Conjures bending a ball's trajectory in games like soccer or cricket."},{"idiom_candidate":"silent timeout","proposed_meaning_en":"a brief pause for reflection or strategic thinking","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"neutral","slang_strength":"none","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Metaphorical use of 'timeout' as a mental breather."},{"idiom_candidate":"climb the scoreboard","proposed_meaning_en":"to steadily gain advantage in a contest","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Imagery of moving upward on a points display."},{"idiom_candidate":"break the huddle","proposed_meaning_en":"to disperse from a group before finalizing plans","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"neutral","slang_strength":"none","regionality":"american","notes":"From football term referring to team gathering before play."},{"idiom_candidate":"catch the draft","proposed_meaning_en":"to gain advantage by riding on momentum or indirect benefit","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"References drafting behind another competitor for speed advantage."},{"idiom_candidate":"skip the whistle","proposed_meaning_en":"to continue pushing forward despite expected stop or limits","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"american","notes":"Suggests ignoring referee calls to maintain momentum."},{"idiom_candidate":"shift the yardline","proposed_meaning_en":"to subtly change position or advantage in a contest","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"american","notes":"Based on American football field yard lines."},{"idiom_candidate":"roll the crossbar","proposed_meaning_en":"to barely miss or nearly achieve a goal","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Crossbar is the goal frame in soccer, 'roll' evokes near contact."},{"idiom_candidate":"drop the down","proposed_meaning_en":"to lose an opportunity or fail at a critical moment","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"american","notes":"From American football with limited attempts (downs) to advance."},{"idiom_candidate":"flash the stripes","proposed_meaning_en":"to show authority or referee-like final say","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Alludes to referee uniforms and power to control game."},{"idiom_candidate":"chase the flag","proposed_meaning_en":"to pursue a penalty or a lost advantage","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"american","notes":"Penalty flags are thrown in American football indicating fouls."},{"idiom_candidate":"pin the broom","proposed_meaning_en":"to cleanly sweep a competition or complete a task flawlessly","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"slang","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"From curling where a broom sweeps the ice."},{"idiom_candidate":"hitch the line","proposed_meaning_en":"to latch onto another’s effort or lead strategically","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Drawing from racing and lines of effort."},{"idiom_candidate":"cycle the gap","proposed_meaning_en":"to exploit openings repeatedly for advantage","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Refers metaphorically to cycling through weak spots."},{"idiom_candidate":"slice the clock","proposed_meaning_en":"to dominate or manage time strategically to win","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"neutral","slang_strength":"none","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Combines time management with slicing imagery."},{"idiom_candidate":"lock the crease","proposed_meaning_en":"to defend a critical position firmly","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"From hockey or cricket, crease is vital area to defend."},{"idiom_candidate":"push the hinges","proposed_meaning_en":"to apply pressure at a pivotal point or moment","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Metaphor for forcing entry or breaking point."},{"idiom_candidate":"flip the jerseys","proposed_meaning_en":"to change sides or allegiances unexpectedly","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Refers to swapping team shirts symbolizing allegiance."},{"idiom_candidate":"snap the net","proposed_meaning_en":"to score decisively or break through defenses","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Net snapping suggests powerful scoring shot."},{"idiom_candidate":"call the sprint","proposed_meaning_en":"to trigger a final push or decisive effort","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"neutral","slang_strength":"none","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Sprint being final burst in a race or competition."},{"idiom_candidate":"hedge the kick","proposed_meaning_en":"to act cautiously in a high-stakes action","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Combines cautious approach with kicking—a decisive move."},{"idiom_candidate":"hold the top rope","proposed_meaning_en":"to maintain control at a crucial position or advantage","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Inspired by wrestling’s top rope position as dominance."},{"idiom_candidate":"drift the post","proposed_meaning_en":"to miss narrowly or lose slight positioning","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Post refers to goalpost or boundary marker."},{"idiom_candidate":"tag the break","proposed_meaning_en":"to mark or take advantage when momentum shifts","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Break as a change in play or opportunity."},{"idiom_candidate":"split the deck","proposed_meaning_en":"to cause division or make a significant strategic move","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"neutral","slang_strength":"none","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Card game metaphor applied to sports tactics."},{"idiom_candidate":"bump the corners","proposed_meaning_en":"to challenge or test rivals at their edges or limits","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Corner bumps are minor jolts or challenges."},{"idiom_candidate":"push the chalk","proposed_meaning_en":"to approach or exceed boundaries or limits","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"american","notes":"Drawing from chalk lines on fields or courts."},{"idiom_candidate":"freeze the clock","proposed_meaning_en":"to halt progress by strategy or control","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Pause the game or moment to retain advantage."},{"idiom_candidate":"sting the buzzer","proposed_meaning_en":"to score or act at the last possible instant","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"american","notes":"Buzzer signifies end of game or time limit."},{"idiom_candidate":"crack the huddle","proposed_meaning_en":"to disrupt or break up a tightly-knit group or plan","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"american","notes":"Huddle is a close team gathering; cracking means breaking it."},{"idiom_candidate":"bulldoze the baseline","proposed_meaning_en":"to aggressively push the limits of a competition area","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Baseline from tennis or basketball, bulldoze for forceful action."},{"idiom_candidate":"surf the whistle","proposed_meaning_en":"to ride the edge of official sanction or rules","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Alludes to staying active until referee stops play."},{"idiom_candidate":"catch the snap","proposed_meaning_en":"to seize a quick opportunity","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"american","notes":"From American football snap to start a play."},{"idiom_candidate":"dart the line","proposed_meaning_en":"to make a swift decisive move along a boundary or limit","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Line is a boundary or marker in play."}          
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"hold the rebound","proposed_meaning_en":"to maintain or regain momentum after a setback","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"neutral","slang_strength":"none","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Rebound is regaining control after a loss or miss."},{"idiom_candidate":"clutch the whistle","proposed_meaning_en":"to seize authority or decisive control in a moment","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Whistle symbolizes power to command or stop action."},{"idiom_candidate":"shove the puck","proposed_meaning_en":"to aggressively push an advantage in a contest","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"From hockey puck control metaphor."},{"idiom_candidate":"flip the cleats","proposed_meaning_en":"to change one’s position or tactics unexpectedly","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Cleats relate to footwear anchoring position or stance."},{"idiom_candidate":"bounce the buzzer","proposed_meaning_en":"to barely gain success before time runs out","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"american","notes":"Buzzer is time end; bouncing meaning to just make it."},{"idiom_candidate":"clear the crease","proposed_meaning_en":"to remove obstacles or opponents from a critical zone","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Crease is vital defensive area in hockey/cricket."},{"idiom_candidate":"run the clock down","proposed_meaning_en":"to use available time slowly to maintain advantage","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"neutral","slang_strength":"none","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Effective time management to secure a lead."},{"idiom_candidate":"sink the spike","proposed_meaning_en":"to make a powerful decisive move or statement","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Spike refers to aggressive volleyball strike or impact."},{"idiom_candidate":"tag the bluff","proposed_meaning_en":"to call out or challenge a false move or tactic","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Bluff meaning feint or fake action."},{"idiom_candidate":"ride the screen","proposed_meaning_en":"to use a setup or support move to advance in competition","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Screen as a block in basketball or other sports."},{"idiom_candidate":"pin the tail","proposed_meaning_en":"to secure a crucial point or finish successfully","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"From 'pin the tail on the donkey', securing an exact spot."},{"idiom_candidate":"flip the pivot","proposed_meaning_en":"to change the central strategy or lead quickly","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Pivot refers to central player or strategy point."},{"idiom_candidate":"bounce the mesh","proposed_meaning_en":"to score or strike with impact, often surprisingly","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Mesh refers to netting of goal or sports bag."},{"idiom_candidate":"draw the whistle","proposed_meaning_en":"to provoke an official’s intervention or penalty","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"To cause the referee to call a foul or stop."},{"idiom_candidate":"stone the clock","proposed_meaning_en":"to completely dominate time or pace of competition","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"'Stone' meaning fully or totally, applied to the clock."},{"idiom_candidate":"snap the chain","proposed_meaning_en":"to break or weaken a connection or defensive line","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Chain referencing linked defense or teamwork."},{"idiom_candidate":"hit the buzzer","proposed_meaning_en":"to finish or achieve something just in time","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"american","notes":"Buzzer signifies end of allowed time."},{"idiom_candidate":"seal the cleat","proposed_meaning_en":"to firmly establish one’s position or control","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Cleat symbolizes footing or grip in competition."},{"idiom_candidate":"crush the baseline","proposed_meaning_en":"to dominate play along a fundamental boundary or area","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Baseline is a key area in many sports."},{"idiom_candidate":"slash the tape","proposed_meaning_en":"to win or finish decisively ahead of others","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Tape refers to finish line tape in races."},{"idiom_candidate":"clutch the rope","proposed_meaning_en":"to desperately hold onto or secure an opportunity","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Rope as a lifeline or boundary in competition."},{"idiom_candidate":"juke the chain","proposed_meaning_en":"to deceive or bypass a sequence of defenses or obstacles","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Chain symbolizes connected defenses."},{"idiom_candidate":"pass the stick","proposed_meaning_en":"to transfer responsibility or lead promptly","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Stick from hockey or lacrosse symbolizing control."},{"idiom_candidate":"hook the play","proposed_meaning_en":"to intercept or derail an opponent’s move","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Hook from hooking an object or player."},{"idiom_candidate":"reach the crossbar","proposed_meaning_en":"to come very close to success but just fall short","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Crossbar is a soccer goalpost upper bar."},{"idiom_candidate":"lock the pivot","proposed_meaning_en":"to control the central point or key player decisively","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Pivot is central element or player in strategy."},{"idiom_candidate":"fling the flag","proposed_meaning_en":"to accuse or challenge an opponent’s illegal tactic","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"american","notes":"Flag is a penalty call marker."},{"idiom_candidate":"surf the snap","proposed_meaning_en":"to move quickly following an abrupt start","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"american","notes":"Snap as quick beginning in American football."},{"idiom_candidate":"bump the net","proposed_meaning_en":"to interfere just slightly and affect the outcome","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Net disturbance as minor but influential act."},{"idiom_candidate":"spin the rebound","proposed_meaning_en":"to quickly capitalize on a second chance","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Rebound is regaining possession after failure."},{"idiom_candidate":"charge the crease","proposed_meaning_en":"to aggressively move into a defended critical zone","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Crease is protected area in hockey or cricket."},{"idiom_candidate":"bounce the board","proposed_meaning_en":"to react quickly or make a comeback","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Board as playing surface or scoreboard."},{"idiom_candidate":"lift the leg","proposed_meaning_en":"to make a bold or risky move to gain advantage","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Leg lift as preparation for action or challenge."}   
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"drop the spike","proposed_meaning_en":"to fail or miss a crucial opportunity","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Spike is a sharp decisive action often successful."},{"idiom_candidate":"push the cones","proposed_meaning_en":"to train intensively or test limits in practice","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Cones as training markers in drills."},{"idiom_candidate":"curl the shot","proposed_meaning_en":"to skillfully curve or manipulate an outcome","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Curl from curling the ball or puck."},{"idiom_candidate":"ride the dime","proposed_meaning_en":"to work closely behind a leader to gain advantage","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"american","notes":"Dime refers to a precise point or spot in football."},{"idiom_candidate":"cut the post","proposed_meaning_en":"to take a shortcut or bold direct move to goal","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Post is part of goal structure or boundary."},{"idiom_candidate":"sweep the mats","proposed_meaning_en":"to decisively win or eliminate an opponent","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Mats from wrestling or martial arts competitions."},{"idiom_candidate":"shove the puck","proposed_meaning_en":"to aggressively control or push forward in a contest","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Puck is the hockey game object controlled by players."},{"idiom_candidate":"climb the ramps","proposed_meaning_en":"to overcome difficult challenges progressively","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Ramps symbolize inclines or obstacles to ascend."},{"idiom_candidate":"tag the pivot","proposed_meaning_en":"to mark or confront a key player or point","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Pivot is central to play or strategy."},{"idiom_candidate":"whip the corner","proposed_meaning_en":"to execute a sharp and skillful maneuver at a critical point","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Corner is often turning point in plays."}  
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"dribble the clock","proposed_meaning_en":"to skillfully use up time to maintain advantage","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"neutral","slang_strength":"none","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Dribble implying slow control over time."},{"idiom_candidate":"split the defense","proposed_meaning_en":"to penetrate or break through opposing resistance","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Defense as opposing players or forces."},{"idiom_candidate":"cross the crease","proposed_meaning_en":"to invade or advance beyond a protected area","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"neutral","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Crease is a designated protected zone."},{"idiom_candidate":"hold the line","proposed_meaning_en":"to maintain position or defend firmly","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"neutral","slang_strength":"none","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Common in sports to describe strong defense."},{"idiom_candidate":"thread the cones","proposed_meaning_en":"to navigate carefully through obstacles or challenges","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Cones used in drills to denote obstacles."}  
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"run the hinges","proposed_meaning_en":"to test or exploit critical points under pressure","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Hinges as pivotal moving points."},{"idiom_candidate":"push the boards","proposed_meaning_en":"to aggressively advance using the perimeter as leverage","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Boards as field/court boundaries, pushing edges."},{"idiom_candidate":"blaze the track","proposed_meaning_en":"to move at an impressive or commanding speed","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Blaze meaning fast or intense motion."},{"idiom_candidate":"pinch the line","proposed_meaning_en":"to compress or press tightly in defense or position","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Pinching means tightening or squeezing."}  
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"shift the pitch","proposed_meaning_en":"to change direction or focus suddenly","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Pitch is playing field; shifting implies repositioning."},{"idiom_candidate":"break the ump","proposed_meaning_en":"to cause controversy or challenge officiating decisions","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"british","notes":"Umpire referee in cricket and other sports."}  
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"curve the shot","proposed_meaning_en":"to skillfully bend or alter the trajectory to achieve success","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"neutral","slang_strength":"none","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Curving a ball or puck to gain advantage."},{"idiom_candidate":"nick the post","proposed_meaning_en":"to just barely miss or impact an edge making a difference","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"british","notes":"From hitting goalposts narrowly in football/soccer."}  
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"hold the timeout","proposed_meaning_en":"to assert control by delaying or pausing strategically","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"neutral","slang_strength":"none","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Timeouts used for regrouping or strategic pauses."},{"idiom_candidate":"roll the puck","proposed_meaning_en":"to move or advance smoothly and strategically","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Puck rolling denotes controlled movement in hockey."},{"idiom_candidate":"lock the pivot","proposed_meaning_en":"to secure control over a central or key position","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Pivot as critical point in strategy or formation."}  
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"switch the cleats","proposed_meaning_en":"to change tactics or position to gain advantage","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Cleats being footwear, symbolizing stance or footing."},{"idiom_candidate":"drag the goalie","proposed_meaning_en":"to take a risk by bypassing a key defender or obstacle","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Goalie is main defensive player in hockey or soccer."}  
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"miss the buzzer","proposed_meaning_en":"to fail to act before a critical deadline","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"american","notes":"Buzzer marks end of allowed time."}  
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"hold the sack","proposed_meaning_en":"to maintain defensive pressure and prevent advancement","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"american","notes":"Sack is when quarterback tackled behind line in football."}  
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"chip the post","proposed_meaning_en":"to score or strike by a delicate or precise action","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"weak","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Chipping is a light, precise kick or shot."}  
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"flatten the pitch","proposed_meaning_en":"to dominate or thoroughly control the playing area","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Pitch is field; flattening implying overwhelming control."}  
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"balance the ball","proposed_meaning_en":"to maintain control and poise under pressure","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"neutral","slang_strength":"none","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Ball control as metaphor for composure."}  
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"curve the track","proposed_meaning_en":"to skillfully navigate a difficult path or challenge","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Track refers to route or course."}  
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"beat the horn","proposed_meaning_en":"to complete an action before a deadline or signal","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"informal","slang_strength":"medium","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Horn often signals end or start in races or contests."}  
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"drop the puck","proposed_meaning_en":"to start or initiate an event or action decisively","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"neutral","slang_strength":"none","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Common ice hockey phrase for starting play."}  
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"step behind the line","proposed_meaning_en":"to take a bold or cautious step while respecting boundaries","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"neutral","slang_strength":"none","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Lines are critical boundaries in sports."}  
  ,{"idiom_candidate":"shift the weight","proposed_meaning_en":"to change position or focus to gain better leverage or advantage","idiom_domain":"sports","idiom_register":"neutral","slang_strength":"none","regionality":"general_english","notes":"Weight shift used metaphorically for tactical adjustments."}  
